properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued January 15 at 4:36AM CST by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
Snow will develop across the area during the mid-day hours, then
diminish by early evening. The snow in central and east-central
Wisconsin could transition to freezing drizzle as it tapers off
late today and this evening. An inch or two of snow accumulation
is expected across most of the area, with 2 to 3 inches possible
in far north-central Wisconsin.

The snow is likely to result in slippery travel conditions.
Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon
commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. Be sure to allow for
some extra travel time once the snow begins

Much colder air will surge into the area overnight as the weather
system producing the snow shifts off to the east. By daybreak
Thursday, temperatures will drop to around zero across central
and north-central Wisconsin, and into the teens along the
Lakeshore. This will drive wind chill indices into the 10 below to
20 below zero range across most of the area, and to 5 below to 10
below along the Lakeshore. Wind chills such as this indicate
exposed skin can suffer frostbite in as little as 30 minutes. Be
sure to dress accordingly before heading out on Thursday morning.

The gusty winds ushering the colder air into the area could
also produce some drifting snow tonight, mainly in rural areas.
Of greater significance is the potential for the rapid arrival of
the colder air to cause any lingering water on the roads to re-
freeze into glare ice and produce very slippery conditions. Be
prepared for the possibility of icy spots on roads and sidewalks
tomorrow morning.

NWSheadline: SNOW EXPECTED TO RESULT IN SLIPPERY TRAVEL CONDITIONS TODAY INTO TONIGHT
